d and emerging young scholars. The book provides a plethora of fresh perspectives and a wealth of new information, suggests enticing avenues for research and – in bringing the whole question of sexual identity to the forefront of debate – challenges us to rethink queer history’s parameters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHomosexualityzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aQueer theoryzGreat BritainxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aBritish art history.  aBritish queer history.  aBritish tabloid press.  aFilm Censorship.  aGender equality.  aJohn Everett Millais.  aSexual Offences Act.  agay pornography.  agossip writing.  ahomophile internationalism.  ahomosexual law reform.  apostwar Britain.  aself-identified lesbians.  asocial practice.  atransnational solidarity.1 aBengry, Justin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeslandes, Paul R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoan, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoulbrook, Matt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Jongwoo Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Brian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLinkof, Ryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinto, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoultonc, Mo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Amy Tooth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUpchurch, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaters, Chris, econtrib